I think you missed the true intent of what I was saying...I'll quote myself, then explain further.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> ...by coincidence of where we usually hunt, we almost never see other players or guilds.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> It is not a goal of myself or my guild to obtain the approval of other people on this server.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
We, as in Magister, do NOT choose our hunting grounds based upon their isolated locations. The nature of the game that we play, the &quot;EQ High End Game&quot;, dictates that few people will be in the same location as us, usually. On rare occasions another guild or groups will share a zone with us. But normally we are alone. <br>
<br>
That has NOTHING to do with a desire by us to avoid other players. Rather it is a coincidence of the fact that most players on this server could not survive to make it to where we hunt. Quite a few can, but most can't. <br>
<br>
As for who I/we try to please in game and in life. In my opinion, 90% of the people in this world just try to please to themselves. To some of them, that means helping other people...feeding and clothing the needy, healing the sick, protecting the weak, caring for loved ones, being a good friend, good lover, and/or a good person. I don't think people do those things because &quot;it's the right thing to do&quot;, I believe that they mostly do those things because it makes them feel good about themselves. <br>
<br>
Some people would not admit to that, but I would. I think most of the people that would not admit to that, at least to a certain extent, are not being honest in their introspective seekings. <br>
<br>
Perhaps I am too philosophical &lt;shrugs&gt; that's the way I am. But if you really want Philsophy...I'll leave you with this. <br>
<br>
&quot;Security is the most vital of all human interests. All other earthly benefits can and will be cheerfully foregone, but security no man can live without.&quot; - John Stuart Mill<br>
